**Explanation:**  
A `debounce` function limits the rate at which a function can fire by delaying its execution until after a specified amount of time has passed since the last invocation.

```javascript
function debounce(func, wait) {
    let timeout;
    return function(...args) {
        const context = this;
        clearTimeout(timeout);
        timeout = setTimeout(() => func.apply(context, args), wait);
    };
}

// Example usage:
window.addEventListener('resize', debounce(() => {
    console.log('Window resized!');
}, 250));
```

In this example, the `debounce` function ensures that the message `'Window resized!'` is logged to the console at most once every 250 milliseconds, no matter how often the window resize event fires.
